== SPONTANEOUS VS DIRECTED PUSHING

How you push matters just as much as what position you're in. There are two main approaches, and they have very different effects.

=== Directed Pushing ("Purple Pushing")

This is what you see in movies: everyone counts to ten while the woman holds her breath and pushes with all her might.

_What it looks like:_
- Take a deep breath
- Hold it
- Push hard for 10 counts
- Quick breath, repeat
- Three pushes per contraction
- Start pushing as soon as you're fully dilated, whether you feel the urge or not

_Why it's called "purple pushing":_ Many women's faces turn purple from the strain of holding their breath while pushing forcefully.

_The problems:_
- Reduces oxygen to baby (you're not breathing) #citation[8]
- More exhausting for you
- Associated with more pelvic floor damage #citation[9]
- Can cause blood vessel damage in your face and eyes #citation[10]
- May not be as effective as following your body's cues

=== Spontaneous Pushing (Following Your Body)

Your body knows how to push out a baby. When you follow its cues instead of external commands, it's called spontaneous or physiologic pushing.

_What it looks like:_
- Wait for the urge to push (even if fully dilated)
- Push when your body tells you to
- Push for as long as feels right (usually 3-5 seconds)
- Breathe when you need to
- Grunt, moan, or vocalize if it helps
- Rest between contractions

_The benefits:_
- Better oxygen to baby
- Less exhausting
- May reduce pelvic floor damage
- Often more effective
- Feels more controlled

=== Why Did Directed Pushing Become Standard?

Directed pushing became common because:
- It speeds things up (slightly) in the short term
- It gives providers something to do
- It works with epidurals (when you can't feel the urge to push)
- It became the cultural norm

But research shows that spontaneous pushing is associated with:#citation[8]
- Similar or shorter total pushing time
- Better outcomes for baby (higher oxygen levels)
- Less pelvic floor trauma
- More satisfying birth experiences

=== Contraction Crest Pushing

One technique worth knowing about is contraction crest pushing, which works with the natural rhythm of your contractions rather than against them. The idea is simple: instead of pushing from the very start of a contraction, you wait until it crests--when the contraction reaches its most intense point, usually about halfway through--and then push. This way, you're working _with_ the involuntary contracting muscles at their strongest, rather than trying to generate all the force yourself.

_How to do it:_
- When you feel a contraction building, take two very deep, slow breaths
- By the end of those two breaths, the contraction will be near its peak
- Begin pushing at that point, riding the wave of the contraction's strongest force
- Stop pushing as the contraction fades

_Why it works:_ Your uterus is already doing a tremendous amount of pushing on its own during a contraction. By timing your voluntary effort to coincide with the peak of that involuntary force, you get maximum effect with less personal effort.#citation[11] Women who use this technique often find pushing far less exhausting than pushing throughout the entire contraction. You're doing less work for more result.

This technique pairs naturally with spontaneous pushing--your body's urge to push tends to align with the contraction crest anyway.

=== What About With an Epidural?

If you have an epidural, you may not feel the urge to push. In this case:
- _"Labor down":_ Wait 1-2 hours after you're fully dilated before starting to push. This lets baby descend on their own.#citation[12]
- _Gentle guidance:_ Your nurse can tell you when you're having a contraction so you know when to push.
- _Avoid prolonged breath-holding:_ Push in shorter bursts with breaths in between.

=== How to Advocate for Spontaneous Pushing

- Tell your nurse: "I'd like to push when I feel the urge rather than being coached."
- Say: "I'd like to try pushing on my own before we start counting."
- If you need some guidance, ask: "Can you just tell me when I'm having a contraction?"

